# Set Up GraphQL / Hasura for a Service

## Arguments
- `service`: Service name that needs Hasura integration
- `tables` (optional): Comma-separated table names to track

## Steps

### 1. Add Hasura SDK Dependency
{{ if .Computed.HasNode }}- Add `{{ .Computed.PrimaryScope }}/hasura-sdk` to the service's `package.json`
- Run `{{ .Project.Spec.Monorepo.PackageManager }} install`{{ end }}

### 2. Create GraphQL Schema Files
- Create `apps/{service}/src/graphql/` directory
- Add `.graphql` query/mutation files for required operations
- Add `codegen.ts` configuration pointing to Hasura endpoint

### 3. Configure Codegen
- Add codegen script to service `package.json`: `"codegen": "graphql-codegen --config codegen.ts"`
- Generated types output to `src/generated/graphql.ts`

### 4. Create Hasura Client
- Create `apps/{service}/src/clients/hasura.ts`
- Initialize with `HASURA_GRAPHQL_URL` and `HASURA_ADMIN_SECRET` from service config
- Export typed client instance

### 5. Track Tables (if specified)
- Run `hasura metadata add-source` if not already configured
- For each table: `hasura metadata track-table <table> --database-name default`
- Set up relationships between tables
- Configure permissions (admin, user roles)

### 6. Add Environment Variables
- Add to service Helm `values.yaml`:
  - `HASURA_GRAPHQL_URL`: `http://hasura.infra.svc.cluster.local:8080/v1/graphql`
  - `HASURA_ADMIN_SECRET`: from external secret or config

### 7. Run Codegen
- Run `{{ .Project.Spec.Monorepo.PackageManager }} nx codegen {service}`
- Verify generated types compile

## Checklist
- [ ] Hasura SDK dependency added
- [ ] GraphQL schema files created
- [ ] Codegen configured and types generated
- [ ] Hasura client initialized in service
- [ ] Tables tracked in Hasura metadata
- [ ] Permissions configured for each table
- [ ] Environment variables set in Helm values
